'''Soda Stereo''' were an [[Argentina | Argentine]] [[rock music | rock]] band from [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]. They were a [[power trio]] made up of singer-songwriter [[Gustavo Cerati]], [[Zeta Bosio|Hector "Zeta" Bosio]] on bass, and Carlos Alberto Ficicchia ([[Charly Alberti]]) on drums. Their career spanned from 1984<U+2013>1997, and was followed up by a short comeback tour in 2007-2008. Soda Stereo began as a new wave outfit influenced by [[The Police]], [[The Specials]], [[Television (band)|Television]], [[The Cure]], [[XTC]], and Argentine rock. Their music evolved toward a heavier [[alternative rock]] sound throughout the 90<U+2019>s, eventually drawing influences from [[classic rock]], [[shoegaze]], and [[Britpop]].

Soda Stereo were the first Latin rock group to achieve success throughout the whole of [[South America|South]] and [[Central America]], where they have sold more than 7 million copies alone. They are considered to be pioneers of the [[Rock En Espa<U+00F1>ol]], Ibero-American Rock, and Latin Rock genres. The band established what would become the template for many other popular [[Hispanophone|Spanish-speaking]] rock music groups. Soda Stereo has topped the all time lists in much of Latin America and in their native [[Argentina]], where they set landmarks in record sales and concert attendances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rock_de_Argentina |title=Rock De Argentina |author= |date= |work=| language = |publisher=wikipedia |accessdate=September 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://rockenlasamericas.blogspot.com/2009/10/mas-que-rock-en-espanollas-120-mejores.html |title=Mas Que Rock En Espa<U+00F1>ol: Las 120 Mejores Canciones del Rock HispanoAmericano de todo Los Tiempos (20-1) (Spanish)|author=Mercado, Jose Luis|date= |work=Rock en las Am<U+00E9>ricas | language = Spanish|publisher= |accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref> In 2002 Soda Stereo was awarded the Legend Prize by [[Los Premios MTV Latinoam<U+00E9>rica|MTV Latin America]], the first prize to be awarded of its kind.

==History==
===From Stereotypes to Soda Stereo (1982-1984)===

[[File:ARA Belgrano sinking.jpg|thumb|The sinking of the Argentinean Cruiser [[ARA General Belgrano|General Belgrano]] in 1982 marked the end of the [[Falklands War]]. The loss of the war caused the Argentinian dictatorship to collapse opening the door for democracy in 1983. It was at that moment that Soda Stereo was born]]

In the summer of 1982 Gustavo Cerati at 22 years of age and Hector Zeta Bosio at 23 years of age collided at [[Punta del Este]], [[Uruguay]]. Cerati with his group ''Sauvage''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lacapital.com.ar/2007/09/21/escenario/noticia_417818.shtml |title=El Comienzo y el Primer Final|author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=La Capital |accessdate=December 8, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and Bosio with ''The Morgan'', a band he shared with [[Sandra Baylac]], Hugo Dop, Christian Hansen, Pablo Rodriguez,([[Los Aut<U+00E9>nticos Decadentes]]), Charly Amato, Osvaldo Kaplan, and [[Andres Calamaro]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imagenanimal.com/biografia/intro/ |title=Biograph<U+00ED>a de Zeta Bosio |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=Imagen Animal |accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref> Cerati and Bosio established a friendship and a musical bond that encourage them to start playing together. Cerati first joined Bosio<U+2019>s group ''The Morgan'', then formed ''Stress'' with Charly Amato and drummer Pablo Guadalupe. He also worked on the project ''Erekto'' with [[Andres Calamaro]]. According to Cerati both projects did not meet his expectations.

At the time Carlos Ficcichia, legal name of [[Charly Alberti]] would incessantly call Cerati's house asking for Maria Laura Cerati, Gustavo<U+2019>s sister. Alberti wanted to ask her out, but she thought he was too <U+201C>pesado<U+201D> (stiff) and did not want to go out with him.<ref name="Lernoud">Lernoud, Pipo: ''Enciclopedia Rock Nacional 30 A<U+00F1>os. De la A a la Z'', page 206. Buenos Aires: Mordisco, 1996. (Spanish)</ref> In one instance when Gustavo answered the phone, they entered a lengthy conversation about music. Alberti mentioned that he was a drummer and the son of the famous [[Jazz]] drummer, [[Tito Alberti]], songwriter of a well known Argentinian children's song, <U+201C>El Elefante Trompita<U+201D> (Little Trunk Elephant).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clarin.com/diario/1998/04/18/c-02401d.htm |title=Tito Alberti: El Otro Baterista |author=Garcia, Fernando |date=April 18, 1998 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=[[diario Clar<U+00ED>n]] |accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref> After hearing Alberti play, they asked him to join the band, but first he had to cut his hair.

After a few experiments (Aerosol, Side Car) the three adopted the name ''Los Estereotipos'' (The Stereotypes), referencing a song by The Specials which they passionately listened to for few months.<ref name="Estereotipos">{{cite web |url=http://www.galeon.com/eltemblor/Historia/1982.html |title=Historia de Soda Stereo: Los Estereotipos |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish |publisher=El Gale<U+00F3>n |accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref> During that time period they record a demo with [[:es:Richard Coleman|Richard Coleman]] on guitars. Soda initially recruited Coleman to beef up the guitar sound but Coleman recognized that the band sounded better without him and quit in good terms, leaving the definitive trio of Gustavo Cerati, Zeta Bosio, and Charly Alberti.<ref name="Lernoud" /> The songs recorded were, <U+201C>Porque No Puedo Ser Del Jet Set?<U+201D> (Why Can<U+2019>t I be Part of the Jet Set?), <U+201C>Dime Sebastian<U+201D> (Tell Me Sebastian), and <U+201C>Debo So<U+00F1>ar<U+201D> (Must Dream) by [[:es:Ulises Butron|Ulises Butr<U+00F3>n]], in which Ulises Butr<U+00F3>n played guitars and [[:es:Daniel Melero|Daniel Melero]] played keyboards. Following that episode, the names <U+201C>Soda<U+201D> and <U+201C>Stereo<U+201D> appeared, which resulted in <U+201C>Soda Stereo.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planetasodastereo.com.ar/a2.htm |title=<U+00BF>C<U+00F3>mo Surgi<U+00F3> El Nombre De La Banda? |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=Planeta Stereo |accessdate=December 14, 2007}}</ref>

Regarding the meaning and use of the word <U+201C>soda:<U+201D>

<blockquote>They say that they make music with bubbles. But instead of referring to luxurious champagne bubbles, they affirm that they assume the representative ordinary and popular [[:es:Sif<U+00F3>n Drago|Sif<U+00F3>n]], or carbonated soft drinks<ref name=sif<U+00F3>n>{{cite web |url=http://www.imagenanimal.com/biografia/1984/ |title=Soda Stereo: Biograf<U+00ED>a: Estalla el sif<U+00F3>n |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=Imagen Animal |accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref></blockquote>

The first show under the name "Soda Stereo" occurred on December of [[1982]]. The occasion was [[:es:Alfredo Lois|Alfredo Lois]] birthday party. Lois was Cerati and Bosio's university classmate. He would go on to become Soda's video director as well as their visual and stylistic guru. Lois was later recognized by Cerati himself as <U+201C>the fourth Soda<U+201D>.<ref name="pepsi">{{cite web |url=http://www.terra.com.ar/canales/Pop_Rock/124/124800.htm |title=''Entrevista en el Pepsi Music Cerati: "A Veces el Rock no Quiere Crecer" |author=Feijoo, Sebastian |date=October 13, 2005 |work= | language = Spanish |publisher= |accessdate=December 8, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

In July 1983 the band made their debut at the discotheque Airport in the [[Buenos Aires]] neighborhood of [[Belgrano (Buenos Aires)|Belgrano]]. According to the band:

<blockquote>Our debut was at a fashion show at the Disco Airport, which was close to where we practiced in Buenos Aires. Nobody gave us a nod. The three of us played on a very deficient sound system. But we were happy, even though no one paid attention. We really looked like a punk group, we didn<U+2019>t know how to play and the sound was loud, even though it was just that<ref name="pepsi"/></blockquote>

Following that gig, Soda Stereo began to play the underground circuit of [[Buenos Aires]], making a name for themselves alongside other emerging bands of the time, such as ''Sumo'', ''Los Twist'', ''Los Encargados'' (with Daniel Melero), and other bands. Soda took up residency at the traditional and deteriorated Cabaret Marab<U+00FA>, located at Maip<U+00FA> 359.<ref name="Lernoud" /> In those early shows, Soda would play songs like <U+201C>H<U+00E9>roes de la Serie<U+201D> (Heroe of the series), <U+201C>La Vi Parada Alli<U+201D> (I saw her standing there), and <U+201C>Vamos a La Playa<U+201D> (Let<U+2019>s go to the beach), along with other songs that appeared on their second demo.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.geocities.com/SunsetStrip/Lounge/6160/HISTORIA.HTM |title=Historia de Soda |author=Pe<U+00F1>a, Jose E. |date= |work= | language = Spanish |publisher= |accessdate=August 30, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/SunsetStrip/Lounge/6160/HISTORIA.HTM&date=2009-10-26+16:56:59|archivedate=2009-10-26}}</ref> On one occasion at the Caf<U+00E9> Einstein, Luca Prodan approached Cerati, whom he considered <U+201C>a chetito,<ref>"A 'chetito' is a somewhat derogatory term used by Argentineans to describe someone from the upper class."</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.elbondi.com/informe/2007-01-01.2133/elinforme.php?cobertura=2133 |title= El Rock De Las Cuatro Esquinas  |author= Andisco, Pablo and B. Lazzaro|date=2007 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher= El Bondi |accessdate=December 17, 2007}}</ref><U+201D> and joined Soda in a cover of a Police song.<ref name="Lernoud" />

The band began to attract a bit of notoriety. One night they were called to a pub to substitute for the group Nylon. There began a period of constant shows which concluded at Bar Zero, a place that excluded the Porte<U+00F1>o underground, along with Caf<U+00E9> Einstein. On their third show, Horacio Martinez, a historic Argentinian rock producer and <U+201C>talent hunter<U+201D> heard them and quickly took them to record for [[CBS]]. This came to fruition in [[1984]] when Soda signed to the Rodr<U+00ED>guez Ares agency.<ref>" Argentinean producer Horacio Mart<U+00ED>nez is credited with the 'discovery' of [[Tanguito]], [[Los Gatos (band)|Los Gatos]] and [[Mauricio "Moris" Birabent|Moris]]".</ref><ref name="Lernoud" />

At the time Soda Stereo was already known as being a band that worked hard on their image and long before the recording of their first album they decided to film a [[video clip]], which they financed with their own money.<ref>[[:es:Alfredo Lois|Alfredo Lois]]</ref> was in charge of the visuals and the graphic designs featured on the fliers and posters for their live performances. It was Alfredo who decided to edit a video clip before the release of the album, something that is quite common today but totally unusual for the time. The song chosen was <U+201C>Diet<U+00E9>tico<U+201D> (Dietitian). The filming was realized with <U+201C>borrowed<U+201D> equipment from Cablevision, where [[Zeta Bosio]] worked as a production assistant.<ref name="Estereotipos" />

===First Album and Chateau Rock '85 (1984-1985)===
[[File:Several television sets.jpg|thumb| "Sobredosis de TV" was chosen as the first single for the first Soda Stereo Album ''Soda Stereo'', released on December 14, [[1984]].The video-clip for "Diet<U+00E9>tico" was aired on M<U+00FA>sica Total on [[Canal 9 (Argentina)|Canal 9]] and had a considerable impact.<ref name="Estereotipos"/>]]

Soda Stereo recorded their debut during the second half of 1984. The album was produced by [[:es:Federico Moura|Federico Moura]], vocalist for [[:es:Virus (banda argentina)|Virus]]. By that time, Moura and Cerati had developed a fruitful artistic relationship. The recording took place in the defunct studios of [[CBS]] on Paraguay street. The end result was cooler sound than of the live shows, which the bands were pleased with. The trio was aided by [[:es:Daniel Melero|Daniel Melero]] on keys and [[:es:Gonzo Palacios|Gonzo Palacios]] on sax. Both were listed as <U+201C>guest musicians,<U+201D> a practice which would become common for Soda throughout their career. Such guest musicians would be recognized by the public as the <U+201C>fourth Sodas<U+201D>.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.zonadepromesasweb.com.ar/Ver-Noticias/soda_stereo_nota_el_cuarto_soda-480/&tipo=Nota&relacion=Soda%20Stereo |title= El Cuarto Soda  |author= |date=2007 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=Rolling Stone Argentina |accessdate=December 8, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

The attention garnered by Soda was manifested in their playing of larger and larger venues. First was <U+201C>La Esquina Del Sol<U+201D> in [[Palermo, Buenos Aires|Palermo]]. <U+201C>El Recital De Los Lagos<U+201D> on the 1st and 2 December was their first multi-headlining show with top Argentinian acts .<ref>Some of the artists who played that show were: [[:es:Virus (banda argentina)|Virus]], [[Juan Carlos Baglietto]], [[:es:GIT|GIT]], [[:es:Su<U+00E9>ter (banda)|Su<U+00E9>ter]], [[:es:Miguel Mateos|Zas]], [[Los Abuelos de la Nada]], [[:es:Marilina Ross|Marilina Ross]], [[:es:Celeste Carballo|Celeste Carballo]], and [[Sandra Mihanovich]].</ref> The show was hosted by Argentinean Television personality [[:es:Juan Alberto Badia|Juan Alberto Bad<U+00ED>a]].

Soda Stereo presented their debut album at El Teatro Astros on the 14th of December 1984, it was their first show there. The stage was designed by Alfredo Lois, who for the occasion located 26 television sets in the background. The TV's were turned on and out of sync with each other - the theme of <U+201C>Sobredosis de TV<U+201D> (TV Overdose). The TV's, together with a large amount of smoke, created an unusual but captivating visual effect<ref name="rock.com.ar">{{cite web |url=http://www.rock.com.ar/bios/0/200.shtml |title= Soda Stereo |author= |date= |work=  | language = Spanish|publisher=Rock.com.ar |accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref>

On the 26th of January 1985 Soda played the Rock in Bali festival in Argentinian port city of [[Mar Del Plata]]. On the 17th of March they played the Festival Chateu Rock <U+2019>85 at the [[Estadio Ol<U+00ED>mpico Chateau Carreras]] in the province of Cordoba. The official biography of the band attach great importance to this appearance indicating that the band played for 15 thousand people and that they were the revelation of the festival.<ref name="oficial">{{cite web |url=http://sodastereo.com/historia/ |title= Soda Stereo: Pagina Oficial: Historia  |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish |publisher= |accessdate=December 10, 2008}}</ref>
However, Cordoba media outlets claim that, "only half the number of people actually showed up and that Soda were hardly noticed because their first record had was just released a few months earlier.<U+201D> They also added <U+201C>[[Raul Porchetto]] was the biggest draw of the night<U+201D>.<ref name="Fernet" >{{cite web |url=http://www2.lavoz.com.ar/nota.asp?nota_id=142196 |title=Fernet Con Soda |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=Diario [[La Voz del Interior]]|accessdate=December 10, 2007}}</ref> Regardless, their presence at Chateau sparked a personal relationship between the band the youth of Cordoba, it marked the moment that the band began to take flight toward national stardom.<ref name="cordoba">{{cite web |url=http://www2.lavoz.com.ar/07/12/01/secciones/espectaculos/nota.asp?nota_id=139629|title= Tras los pasos de Soda Stereo en C<U+00F3>rdoba  |author= |date=December 7, 2001 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher= Diario [[La Voz del Interior]]|accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref>

The success of the band began at a very pecuiliar time, related, on the one hand with the [[Ra<U+00FA>l Alfons<U+00ED>n|return of democracy to Argentina]] (December 10, 1983), and on the other hand, with increasing notions of [[postmodernism]], particularly in the way the 80<U+2019>s youth created their role in a newly democratic society, one that had just emerged from bloody [[Dirty War|Dictatorship]] and [[Falklands War|War]].

Years later, [[Zeta Bosio]] would reflect on this juncture:

<blockquote>The democracy produced the adrenalin of something new, something was occurring, I knew I was going to make changes without knowing how. There was more air for us to make things and to wander, and we were a band of kids that wanted to make trouble. Our attention was on punk and on trying to show that there was something else that was more direct<ref name="cordoba">{{cite web |url= http://www.desdeabajoweb.com.ar/soda.htm |title= Informe Especial: Soda Stereo (Spanish) |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Desde Abajo Diario [[La Voz del Interior]]|accessdate=December 8, 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071026033539/http://www.desdeabajoweb.com.ar/soda.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = October 26, 2007}}</ref></blockquote>

On the 13th of October of that year, Soda played in front of a large audience in Buenos Aires as part of the third night of the Festival of Rock and Pop Held at the [[Estadio Jos<U+00E9> Amalfitani|Jos<U+00E9> Amalfitani Stadium]] home of the soccer club [[Club Atl<U+00E9>tico V<U+00E9>lez S<U+00E1>rsfield|Velez Sarsfield]] . They shared the stage with [[INXS]], [[Nina Hagen]], [[Charly Garcia]], [[:es:Virus (banda argentina)|Virus]], and [[:es:Sumo (banda)|Sumo]], among others. By then Fabian <U+201C>V<U+00F6>n<U+201D> Quintero and Gonzo Palacios were <U+201C>stable guests.<U+201D>

===Nada Personal and Obras 1985-1986===

[[File:423744318 1448f9577f b.jpg|thumb|The Video for ''Cuando pase el temblor'' (When The Earthquake Passes) (1986), directed by [[Alfredo Lois]] was filmed at the [[Inca Empire|Incan]] ruins of [[Pucar<U+00E1> de Tilcara]], in [[Jujuy]]. Soda fused rock and [[carnavalito]] (traditional Andean music. The video was nominated as the finalist for the 12th World Festival of Video and TV in [[Acapulco]].]]

Soda<U+2019>s second <U+00E1>lbum [[:es:Nada personal (<U+00E1>lbum)|Nada Personal]] was edited on October of [[1985]]. During the summer the group toured the touristic centers of Argentina, playing in [[Mar de Plata]], [[Villa Gesell]], and [[Pinamar]]. Finalizing the tour with a consecrating concert at the Festival De la Falda in [[C<U+00F3>rdoba, Argentina|C<U+00F3>rdoba]], which featured [[Andres Calamaro]] and [[Charly Garc<U+00ED>a]] on keyboards on <U+201C>Jet Set.<U+201D>

In April the band decided to officially present the album at a concert at the [[Arena Obras Sanitarias|Estadio Obras Sanitarias]] in [[Buenos Aires]]. There they realized four historic shows with a total attendance of 20,000 spectators. Footage from the first show was edited into a long play video.,<ref>[[:es:Bobby Flores|Bobby Flores]]</ref> the noted music critic and founder of the groundbreaking Rock & Pop Radio in Buenos Aires, thus ending his chronicle of the concert, had this to say:

"We are facing the most powerful group in the country ... The best parameter to measure this presentation is that it was short, it seemed to have lasted ten minutes or so and people were left wanting more. The outpouring of the stadium was a general murmur of the songs from Soda Stereo. The rain, the traffic on [[Avenida del Libertador]] was cluttered by those entering and leaving. The last hot dog of the night and a healthy sense of well being, leave no room for existential questions. I then put my jaw back in place and went singing softly <U+201C>Estoy Azulado<U+201D> between the rain on  Libertador.<ref name="obras">{{cite web |url=http://www.zonadepromesasweb.com.ar/Ver-Noticias/soda_stereo_nota_temblor_en_obras-95/Pagina_4/&relacion=Soda%20Stereo |title=Temblor en Obras |author=Flores, Bobby |date=April 11, 1986 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=Revista Rock & Pop |accessdate=December 8, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>"

After these concerts records sales began to increase at an accelerated rate, quickly passing the [[Gold certification]] that they had achieved during the summer, [[platinum certification]], and finally double platinum in the following months. Without abandoning the danceable rhythms, the second LP resulted in more depth in the lyrics and a melodical maturity. The album marked the definitive consecration of Soda Stereo to the Argentenian public.

