=== The Conquest of Latin America (1986-1989) ===

[[File:Vi<U+00F1>a 2006 - 2do d<U+00ED>a.JPG|thumb|In [[1986]] [[Chile|Chilean Youth]] received Soda Stereo as popular idols. The song that created this first contact was [[:es:Nada personal (canci<U+00F3>n)<U+201C>Nada|Personal<U+201D>]] (Nothing Personal) which became a radio hit. A little later in February of [[1987]] Soda a has a strong showing at the [[Vi<U+00F1>a del Mar International Song Festival]], again in Chile. This, in effect, opened the doors to the rest of Latin America.<ref name="">{{cite web |url=http://www.galeon.com/eltemblor/Historia/1986.html |title=1986: America es de Soda |author= |date= |work= |language= Spanish |publisher=El Gale<U+00F3>n |accessdate=December 8, 2007 }}</ref>]]

In 1986 Soda Stereo realized their first Latin American tour, called Signos - still touring with the Nada Personal record. The band played in [[Colombia]], [[Costa Rica]] [[Peru]], and [[Chile]] with considerable success. In Chile they realized four shows in [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], on the 21,22,24, and 25 November, and one in [[Valpara<U+00ED>so]] on the 22nd of November of 86  In November 1986 Soda arrived in Peru for the first time and revolutionized the market. Their album sales were enormous and their three shows at the Amauta Coliseum were unforgettable.

At that time Latin Rock was not that popular with the youth of Latin America (with the exceptions of [[Argentina]] and [[Uruguay]]) and bands were not accustomed to international tours.<ref name="Bailando">{{cite web |url= http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/suplementos/radar/9-191-2002-05-12.html |title= Bailando Sobre Los Escombros de Carlos Polimeni |author=Zeiger, Claudio |date=May 12, 2002 |work= | language = Spanish |publisher= |accessdate=December 8, 2007}}</ref>

On the 10th of November of [[1986]] the band released their third album ''[[Signos]]''. ''[[Signos]]'' with its lead single [[:es:Persiana Americana|"Persiana Americana"]] (American Blinds) was a key step for Soda Stereo who by now had come under a great deal of stress due to ever increasing factors: sales expectations, external pressures, the risk of failure, and internal tensions. The band was joined in the studio by [[:es:Fabi<U+00E1>n V<U+00F6>n Quintiero|Fabi<U+00E1>n V<U+00F6>n Quintiero]] on keys, [[:es:Richard Coleman|Richard Coleman]] on guitar and [[:es:Celsa Mel Gowland|Celsa Mel Gowland]] on back up vocals. Signos became the first Argentinian Rock album to be released on Compact Disc. It was manufactured in the Netherlands and distributed throughout Latin America.<ref name="signos">{{cite web |url= http://www.zonadepromesasweb.com.ar/Soda_Stereo/Discografia/Oficiales/Signos/|title= Sitio No Oficial de Soda Stereo. Discograf<U+00ED>a: Signos |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish|publisher= Zona de Promesas |accessdate=December 8, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

On the 3rd of December Soda made their first appearance in Ecuado. In early 1987 Soda returned to Chile, this time to the [[Vi<U+00F1>a del Mar International Song Festival]] where they won the prize <U+201C>Antorcha de Plata<U+201D> (Silver Torch). The festival was broadcasted via television to many Latin American countries, expanding the band<U+2019>s fame throughout the continent. It did not take long to transform itself into a massive unconditional adhesion which was called <U+201C>Sodamania<U+201D>.

On the 23rd of April 1987, Soda broke records for ticket sales in [[Paraguay]] with their show at the Yacht Club. Meanwhile ''[[Signos]]'' reached Platinum status in [[Argentina]], triple platinum in [[Per<U+00FA>]] and double platinum in [[Chile]].Soda<U+2019>s first show in Mexico occurred on the 4th of August in 1987 at the Magic Circus in [[Mexico City]]. Soda

The Signos tour was a milestone for Soda as they played 22 concerts in 17 cities to almost 350,000 fans, in the process opening up the idea that Latin Rock can transcend the nationalities of the bands, something that would come to fruition in the upcoming decade. With live recordings from different shows, a live album Ruido Blanco was compiled in 1987. Mixed in Barbados, it was considered by [[Rolling Stone]] (Argentina) to be one of the top 5 live albums of Argentinean Rock<ref name="top 5 live">{{cite web |url= http://my-musik.com/article3953.html |title= Top 10 Discos En Vivo Argentinos |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish|publisher= Rolling Stone (Argentina) |accessdate=December 9, 2007}}</ref>

In late [[1988]] Soda began to work on a new album alongside Puerto Rican producer [[Carlos Alomar]]. Alomar had worked with [[David Bowie]], [[Mick Jagger]], [[Simple Minds]], [[Iggy Pop]], and [[Paul McCartney]], among others. ''[[Doble Vida]]'' (Double Life) was recorded and mixed in [[New York City]]. It was the first record by an Argentinean band to be completely recorded abroad.<ref>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r101373|pure_url=yes}} |title=Doble Vida (Overview) |author=Adaime, Iv<U+00E1>n|date= |work= |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=April 1, 2007}}</ref>

The album produced four singles, "Picnic en el 4B" (Picnic in Room 4b), "En la Ciudad de la Furia" (In the City of Fury), and "Lo Que Sangra (La C<U+00FA>pula)" (That Which Bleeds (The Dome), and <U+201C>Corazon Delator<U+201D> ([[The Tell-Tale Heart|Tell-Tale Heart]]). The video for <U+201C>En La Ciudad de La Furia<U+201D> was a finalist for an [[MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Award]] in the category of best foreign video (there was no Latin MTV at the time).

After more than a year without playing in Buenos Aires, Soda showcased ''[[Doble Vida]]'' at the hockey field at Obras in front of 25,000 fans. To top of a stellar year, Soda headlined the Three Days for Democracy Festival, which took place in Buenos Aires on the intersection of Avenida del Libertador and Nueve De Julio. The show was attended by 150,000 people and Soda shared the stage with [[Luis Alberto Spinetta]] [[Fito P<U+00E1>ez]], [[Los Ratones Paranoicos]], [[:es:Man Ray (grupo)|Man Ray]], and others.

With sales of a million copies of ''[[Doble Vida]]'' under their belt, Soda began a massive tour in early [[1989]]. The tour began with 30 shows in Argentina, covering most of the country, which were attended by nearly 270,000 thousand fans. These shows were followed by a new Latin American tour (their third), which cemented a massive following in [[Mexico]].

Near the end of 1989 Soda records a new version of <U+201C>Languis<U+201D> (from ''[[Doble Vida]]'') and a new song titled <U+201C>Mundo de Quimeras<U+201D> (World of Chimeras). Both songs were released in the EP Languis (1989) along with remixes of <U+201C>En El Borde<U+201D> and <U+201C>Lo Que Sangra (La C<U+00FA>pula)<U+201D>. Following the release of Languis Soda played two sold out shows at The Palace in [[Los Angeles]], becoming the second [[Rock en Espa<U+00F1>ol]] to play in the [[United States]], following [[Miguel Mateos]].

=== The Consecration: Canci<U+00F3>n animal (1990-1991) ===

[[File:SodaStereo CancionAnimal.jpg|thumb|The album ''[[Canci<U+00F3>n Animal]]'', released in [[1990]], is considered to be one of the best albums of all time of the Latin Rock genre.]]

In early 1990 the band co-headlined a show for 32,000 people with British new wave band [[Tears for Fears]] at the [[Estadio Jos<U+00E9> Amalfitani|Jose Amalfitani Stadium]] in Buenos Aires.

Soda Stereo then traveled to Criteria Studios in [[Miami, Florida]] to begin work on their fifth album. They would enlist the help of [[:es:Daniel Melero|Daniel Melero]], [[:es:Andrea <U+00C1>lvarez|Andrea <U+00C1>lvarez]], and [[Tweety Gonz<U+00E1>lez]] (all very important figures in the Argentinian rock scene of the time.

The resulting album ''[[Canci<U+00F3>n Animal]]''(1990) is considered to be one of the best albums in the history of Latin rock. It contains their most well known song <U+201C>[[De M<U+00FA>sica Ligera]]<U+201D> (Of Light Music), as well as other classics such as <U+201C>Cancion Animal<U+201D> (Animal Song), <U+201C>Un Million de A<U+00F1>os Luz<U+201D> (A Million Light Years), <U+201C>En el Septimo Dia<U+201D> (On the Seventh Day), and <U+201C>Te Para Tres<U+201D> (Tea For Three). These songs are considered to be the band's strongest and at the same time are their most popular,.<ref name="amgca">{{cite web | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=r101372|pure_url=yes}} | title = ''Canci<U+00F3>n Animal'' > Overview | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | last = Adaime | first = Iv<U+00E1>n | work = [[Allmusic]] }}</ref> Overall, the album is considered as the most consistent work by the band, along with ''Signos''.<ref name="amgca" />

Their Massive Tour ''Animal'' (1990<U+2013>1991) included 30 Argentinean cities, many which had not been visited by a band with the reach of Soda Stereo. The cities visited in Argentina were:  [[San Juan, Argentina|San Juan]], [[Santa Fe de la Vera Cruz]], Jun<U+00ED>n, [[Clorinda, Formosa|Clorinda]], [[Puerto Iguaz<U+00FA>]], [[Trelew]], [[Neuqu<U+00E9>n]], Santa Rosa, [[Trenque Lauquen]] [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]], [[C<U+00F3>rdoba, Argentina|C<U+00F3>rdoba]], [[R<U+00ED>o Cuarto, C<U+00F3>rdoba|R<U+00ED>o Cuarto]], [[Santiago del Estero]], [[San Miguel de Tucum<U+00E1>n]], [[Salta]], [[Rosario, Santa Fe|Rosario]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[Olavarria]], [[Pergamino]]. International cities included: [[Santiago de Chile]], [[Asuncion del Paraguay]], [[Punta del Este]], [[Barquisimeto]], [[Caracas]], Valencia, [[M<U+00E9>rida, M<U+00E9>rida|M<U+00E9>rida]], San Crist<U+00F3>bal, [[Mexico City]], [[Monterrey, Mexico|Monterrey]], [[Guadalajara]], [[Mexicali]], and [[Tijuana]].

The Tour ''Animal'' finished with 14 consecutive shows at the Grand Rex Theater in [[Buenos Aires]]. With a 3,300 person capacity, this was a noticeable achievement at the time.<ref>two years later [[Sandro de Am<U+00E9>rica|Sandro]] would play 40 consecutive shows at the Grand Rex</ref> Some of the Grand Rex shows would appear on the live EP ''Rex Mix'' (1991), which included remixed versions of a new song, <U+201C>No Necesito Verte (Para Saberlo)<U+201D> (I don<U+2019>t Need to See You - To Know).

[[File:Buenos Aires-Av. 9 de julio.jpg|thumb|left|La [[Avenida 9 de Julio (Buenos Aires)|Avenida 9 de Julio]] en [[Buenos Aires]]. On December 14, [[1991]] Soda gave a free concert here to more than 250,000 people.]]

By late 1991 Soda<U+2019>s continental success brought the band to the attention of MTV News Europe who began to take notice of what was taking place in Latin America, particularly with [[Rock en Espa<U+00F1>ol]]. MTV unconditionally dedicated a whole show to Soda - a first for non English singing band.<ref name="Costa">{{cite web |url=http://aerosoda.spaces.live.com/Blog/cns!162B7F502C77AB90!597.entry |title= Soda Stereo: 1982 - 2007, Me Ver<U+00E1>s Volver |author=Kon, Daniel and Robert Costa |date=Oct 10, 2007 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher= Aerosoda |accessdate=December 9, 2007}}</ref>

In May 1992 Soda embarked on a tour of Spain with shows in [[Madrid]], [[Oviedo]], [[Sevilla]], [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]], and [[Barcelona]].The lackluster results of the Spanish tour, compared to the fervor they were accustomed to in Latin America, left a sour taste in their mouths. Nevertheless, it did serve as a valid experience, specifically in bringing the band back to earth. To put it bluntly: Spain was in no way a failure, but was far from the success that Soda had been used to in Latin America, in the end it was a good learning experience.<ref name="Costa" />

===The Experimentation: Dynamo (1992-1994)===

After that moment, Soda came to the realization that they were at the center of the scene. Therefore, they decided to give some space to the musical experimentation and openly propel what would be known as ''La Movida Sonica'' (The Sonic Movement). Nearing the end of 1992 Soda released their sixth studio album ''[[Dynamo (Soda Stereo album)|Dynamo]]''. ''Dynamo'' was christened with six concerts at Obras. Each show featured a different band as support, [[Babasonicos]], [[:es:Juana La Loca (banda)|Juana La Loca]], [[:es:17 caramelos|Martes Menta]] and [[:es:Tia Newton|Tia Newton]], The Sonic Movement of which [[:es:Demonios de Tasmania|Demonios de Tasmania]] and [[:es:Los Brujos|los Brujos]] would also be part of. This would be derivative of something called <U+201C>El Nuevo Rock Argentino" (The New Argentinian Rock).,<ref>[[:es:Attaque 77|Attaque 77]]</ref> [[:es:Massacre|Massacre]], and [[El Otro Yo]] were also considered part of the movement.<ref name="Perez">{{cite web |url= http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/suplementos/radar/9-3960-2007-07-20.html |title= Mucho M<U+00E1>s Que Cero  |author=Perez, Martin |date=July 20, 2007 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher= |accessdate=December 10, 2007 }}</ref> The band also showcased the album in its entirety in a local talk-show, ''Fax''. This was the first [[Stereophonic sound|stereophonic]] TV transmission in Argentina.<ref name="rock.com.ar"/>

According to Gustavo Cerati, ''Dynamo'' consisted of taking ''[[Canci<U+00F3>n Animal]]'' and destroying it." Cerati explains, "It is as if we took ''[[Canci<U+00F3>n Animal]]'' and put it under water. And, a at a sonic level, we wanted to produce that, the songs had more to do with something hypnotic. The idea was to remix it, to mix it with something more dance and include something more trance in our music. I know that those who understood that record loved it and it is the same with me.<ref name="pepsi"/>

According to AllMusic ''Dynamo'',was Soda's least popular album and at the same time their most experimental work.<ref>{{cite web | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=r176493|pure_url=yes}} | title = ''Dynamo'' Overview | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | last = Adaime | first = Iv<U+00E1>n | work = [[Allmusic]] }}</ref> Dynamo did not sell as expected, in large part because the band decided to change record company immediately after recording it. Sony at the time, had no intentions of promoting a group that had just emigrated from BMG and BMG could not promote another foreign product.

In January of 1993 Soda began their sixth tour of [[Latin America]], visiting [[Mexico]], [[Chile]], [[Paraguay]], and [[Venezuela]]. During the middle of the tour, the trio decided to take a long rest which fueled rumors of a break up. There had been talk of dates in the [[United States]], [[Spain]] and other countries, but diverse factors during late [[1993]] and early [[1994]] forced the group to take a <U+201C>rest<U+201D> from Soda Stereo.

[[1994]] was the worst year for Soda. On the 4th of July, Zeta<U+2019>s two young sons died in an absurd transit accident in Argentina. This event would deeply affect Zeta on both a personal and professional level. By unanimous decision Soda decided to distance themselves from the myth for a while and at the same time to evaluate the possibility of a definitive separation.

During this hiatus, Gustavo released his first solo project: ''[[Amor Amarillo]]'' (Yellow Love), (ironically, Gustavo had mentioned that he had no interest in a solo career). Zeta dedicated himself to the production of other pands (Peligrosos Gorriones and Aguirre). Charly disappeared from the music scene to focus on personal projects.

At the end of 1994 ''[[Zona de Promesas]]'', a compilation of remixes and classic Soda songs, including the unreleased song that gave the album its name, was released,

=== Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo (Stereo Dream) (1995-1997)===

[[File:Sue<U+00F1>oStereo.jpg|thumb|In [[1995]] Soda Release ''[[Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo]]'', the last of their 7 studio albums. In this album the [[Loudspeaker|speaker]] was utilized as a powerful [[symbol]]: the cover contains three speakers (a bigger one in the middle), posing as ovules surrounded by spermatozoa speakers. The image of the speaker is also used in the video for [[Ella us<U+00F3> mi cabeza como un rev<U+00F3>lver]] ("She Used My Head Like a Revolver")<ref name="SStereo">{{cite web |url=http://www.coveralia.com/caratulas/Soda-Stereo-Sueno-Stereo-Frontal.php |title=Tapa De Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo |author= |date= |work= |language= Spanish |publisher=Coveralia |accessdate=December 10, 2007 }}.</ref>]]

After a three year absence, on the 29th of June 1995, Soda release [[Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo]] (Stereo Dream), their 7th and final studio album. The album was an instant hit quickly reaching [[Music recording sales certification|platinum disc]] in Argentina 15 days after its release.<ref name="sslabanda">{{cite web | url = http://www.sodastereo.com/labanda/index.html | title = La banda | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | work = Soda Stereo official website | language = Spanish | archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060424034444/http://www.sodastereo.com/labanda/index.html | archivedate = 2006-04-24 }}</ref> The album was powered by the radio hit <U+201C>Zoom<U+201D> and the promotional video for [[:es:Ella us<U+00F3> mi cabeza como un rev<U+00F3>lver|<U+201C>Ella Uso Mi Cabeza Como Un Revolver<U+201D>]] (She Used My Head Like a Revolver), which in 1996 won the viewers choice award presented by [[MTV]] Latin America. This was a maximum accolade given that this award at the time, since the actual award would not be established until 2002 for Latin MTV.

According to Cerati:

<blockquote>Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo took two years to conceive. It would be illogical to say that this was Soda<U+2019>s masterpiece, but it was the most real expression by the group at the time, because we were stripped of the need of having a group in the future, or of being the best for another ten years. We had already passed through a lot of things and the band itself felt classic. On the other hand, we were very proud of what Dynamo had promoted and its subsequent interpretation. Then, Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo had the pressure of not pressuring us. The band had to deliver something important, it couldn<U+2019>t be a little record. Besides, we had to find ourselves again after a while and allow the music to flow, without thinking too much about taking or step or something like that. In the end, Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo is one of the most innovative records of our career, without us trying to make it so -because of its sonic combinations, its lyrics, and because of its sound.<ref name="pepsi"/></blockquote>

The <U+00E1>lbum b<U+00E9>came the axis for the extensive Gira Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo (Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo Tour), which began on September 8 in [[Buenos Aires]], at the Grand Rex Theater. It covered [[Venezuela]], [[Colombia]], [[Per<U+00FA>]], [[Panam<U+00E1>]], [[M<U+00E9>xico]] and the [[United States]] ([[Los Angeles]], [[Chicago]], [[New York]], and [[Miami]]). The tour finished on the 24th of April of [[1996]] at the Teatro Telet<U+00F3>n in [[Santiago De Chile]].

In mid [[1996]] Soda was invited to Miami by [[MTV]] to record a session for MTV's acoustic show, [[MTV Unplugged]]. After a few refusals by the band, Soda was able to convince the network to accept an offer where the band would play plugged in, but with modifications such as orchestration including new arrangements of some of their classic songs. The result was an eclectic mix of music, some electric, some acoustic, but all bearing the Soda Signature style. A highlight of the album was a soaring rendition of <U+201C>En La Ciudad De La Furia.<U+201D> where the chorus was sung by [[Andrea Echeverri]] of the Colombian [[Rock en Espa<U+00F1>ol]] band [[Aterciopelados]]. Other songs recorded were, <U+201C>Un Misil en Mi Placard,<U+201D> <U+201C>Entre Canibales,<U+201D> <U+201C>Cuando Pase El Temblor,<U+201D> T<U+00E9> Para Tres,<U+201D> <U+201C>Angel Electrico,<U+201D> <U+201C>Terapia de Amor Intensiva,<U+201D> <U+201C>Disco Eterno,<U+201D> <U+201C>Ella Us<U+00F3> Mi Cabeza Como Un Rev<U+00F3>lver,<U+201D> <U+201C>Paseando Por Roma, Y <U+201C>G<U+00E9>nesis<U+201D> (A cover of Vox Dei). The recording of the [[MTV]] show were partially released on the album ''[[Comfort Y M<U+00FA>sica Para Volar]]'' (Comfort and Music to Fly By) ([[1996]]), and in its entirety in a new version of Comfort released in 2007. The album cointained 4 new tracks from the [[Sue<U+00F1>o Stereo]] sessions as well as an interactive cd-rom with pictures and videos from the show.

On the 30th of October of [[1996]] Soda Stereo became the first Latin American band to transmit a live concert via the internet, via the Argentinian radio program Cu<U+00E1>l Es? (Which is?). The show was conducted by [[Mario Pergolini]] on Argentina Rock & Pop radio. The band played live from the music store Prom<U+00FA>sica in BuenoS Aires.<ref name="Rock.mx">{{cite web |url= http://www.rock.com.mx/soda_01_07.html |title= A Una D<U+00E9>cada De Su Despedida Los Veremos Volver  |author= |date= |work= | language = Spanish |publisher= |accessdate=December 10, 2007 }}</ref>

===Band Breakup (1997) ===
A long silence preceded the final farewell, except for band<U+2019>s participation on a Rock En Espa<U+00F1>ol Tribute album, [[:es:Tributo a queen|Tribute a Queen: Los Grandes del Rock en Espa<U+00F1>ol]]. Soda covered <U+201C>Someday One Day,<U+201D> from Queen<U+2019>s 1974 album, Queen II , and sung it in Spanish, as <U+201C>Algun Dia.<U+201D>

Finally, in May 1997 Soda Officially announced their separation through a press release. The following day, Argentiniean newspapers echoed the news. The Argentinian daily [[:es:Diario Clar<U+00ED>n|Clar<U+00ED>n]] devoted a large front page spread to the breakup. The following day, Gustavo Cerati's farewell note was published on the Clar<U+00ED>n supplement for juveniles <U+201C>Yes.<U+201D> The farewell letter read:

<blockquote>These lines were inspired from what I have seen on the street these days, fans who have approached me, the people around me, and from my own personal experience. I share the sadness that has been created in many by our separation. I, myself, am immersed in that state because few things have been so important to me in my life as Soda Stereo. Everyone knows that it is impossible to lead a band without a certain level of conflict. It is a fragile equilibrium in the battle of ideas that very few are able to handle for fifteen years, as we proudly did. But, ultimately, different personal and musical misunderstandings began to compromise that equilibrium. At that juncture, excuses are generated for not confronting ourselves, excuses for a future group that we no longer believed in as we did in the past. To end for the heatlh of the band is, in its redundancy, to enforce value our mental health and above all to show respect for all of our fans who followed us for such a long time. A big hug.<ref name="letter">{{cite web |url=http://www.rpp.com.pe/portada/entretenimiento/101614_1.php
 |title= La Carta Del Adi<U+00F3>s |author=Cerati, Gustavo |date=May 2, 1997 |work= | language = Spanish |publisher=Diario Clar<U+00ED>n |accessdate=December 20, 2007}}</ref></blockquote>

The band carried on with a farewell tour, making stops in [[Mexico]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Chile]]. Their last concert took place on 20 September at the [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti|River Plate Stadium]] in Buenos Aires was recorded and released in two parts, ''[[El <U+00DA>ltimo Concierto]]'' A and B.<ref name="nacion">{{cite news | url = http://www.lanacion.com.ar/77304 | title = Tom<U+00E1>telo con Soda | accessdate = 2007-02-07 | date = 1997-09-22 | work = [[La Naci<U+00F3>n]] | language = Spanish | first = Adriana | last = Franco}}</ref> A DVD of the farewell show was released in 2005. The show ended with the song <U+201C>De Musica Ligera<U+201D> and a memorable farewell by Cerati,

<blockquote><U+201C><U+00A1>No s<U+00F3>lo no hubi<U+00E9>ramos sido nada sin ustedes, sino con toda la gente que estuvo a nuestro alrededor desde el comienzo; algunos, siguen hasta hoy! <U+00A1>Gracias.... totales!<U+201D></blockquote>

<blockquote><U+201C>We would have not been anything without you, if not with all of the people that were around us since the beginning; some continue till this day, thank you... totally!<U+201D></blockquote>

A compilation CD was released later that year titled ''[[:es:Chau Soda|Chau Soda]]'' ("Bye Soda"); it contains the most elaborated version of ''[[Signos]]''.

===Post Soda===
Regardless of the constant rumors of a reunion, which ironically started shortly after the breakup, little was heard regarding Soda, except for a TV special on <U+201C>El Ultimo Concierto<U+201D> (The Last Concert) produced by HBO and an MTV documentary titled Soda Stereo: La Leyenda (Soda Stereo: The Legend). Finally, in 2002 the trio was reuinited at the [[Los Premios MTV Latinoam<U+00E9>rica|MTV Latin Music Video Awards]] where they were awarded the Legend award in honor of their musical and visual trajectory.

Seven years after the breakup and the absence of any new official releases seemed odd. Near the end of 2003 [[Sony Music]] announced the release of the first DVD by Soda Stereo, on that contained much unreleased material from compiled by Gustavo, Zeta, Charly, and people close to the band.

The finished product arrived on the streets on November 2004. It was titled, Soda Stereo: Una Parte de La Euforia(1983<U+2013>1997) (Soda Stereo: A Part of the Euphoria (1983<U+2013>1997)). On September 20, 2005 an Argentinian DVD of Soda<U+2019>s last concert, which took place exactly 8 years before at River Plate stadium was released. It was titled El Ultimo Concierto (En Vivo) (The Last Concert <U+2013> Live). The [[DVD]], in contrast to the [[HBO]] production, featured a 5.1 audio and included two songs that were not aired on the HBO concert, <U+201C>Juego de Seduccion<U+201D> and <U+201C>Sobredosis de TV.<U+201D> It also included a multi camera option for a soundcheck of <U+201C>Primavera 0<U+201D> and a 25 minute documentary about the tour featuring footage of sound checks and concerts in [[Mexico]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Argentina]]. It also featured an interview with the long lost <U+201C>fourth Soda<U+201D> [[:es:Alfredo Lois|Alfredo Lois]], the director of the DVD, one his last works before his death.

=== You Will See Me Return(2007)===
[[File:Entradasoda.jpg|thumb|[[Gira Me ver<U+00E1>s volver|<U+00AB>Me ver<U+00E1>s Volver<U+00BB>]]. Ticket for the [[Bogot<U+00E1>]] (Colombia) show. Soda Stereo reuinited one million fans during their 2007 reunion tour.]]

The reunification of Soda stereo was a mandatory topic for journalists whenever faced with a former member. So much so, that Zeta Bosio once declared:

One day I dreamed that I was not going to be asked about a Soda reunion!.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.clarin.com/diario/2007/02/18/espectaculos/c-01365463.htm |title= Zeta Bosio: No Encontr<U+00E9> Nuevos Socios |author= |date=February 18, 2007 |work= | language = Spanish|publisher=Clar<U+00ED>n |accessdate=December 20, 2007 }}</ref>

In [[2007]], ten years after the breakup, the band decides to reunite for one time with the goal of accomplishing a grand continental tour. On the 6th of June 2007, the official news came out: Soda Stereo will return to the stage with a sole American tour called ''Me Veras Volver'' (You Will See Me Return), a phrase that<U+2019>s emblematic of their song <U+201C>En La Ciudad de la Furia<U+201D>

In early July Sony/BMG released a new compilation album titled ''Me Ver<U+00E1>s Volver (Hits & +)''. The CD contained 18 studio recordings remastered in 2007. The CD did not contain any new material but it did contain a code to receive exclusive web footage such as live versions. The album reached number one in [[Argentina]] and in [[Chile]].<ref name="">{{cite web |url=http://www.rpp.com.pe/portada/entretenimiento/musica_y_conciertos/103476_1.php|title= Soda Stereo Regresa a Lista de Discos M<U+00E1>s Vendidos de Am<U+00E9>rica Latina |author= |date=November 8, 2007 |work= | language = Spanish |publisher= RPP Noticias |accessdate=December 12, 2007}}</ref>

On the 20th of September 2007, exactly 10 years since their final concert, Soda Stereo gave a long awaited press conference at the Club Museum in Peru, in a historical building designed at the turn of the century by the famous French architect and structural engineer [[Gustave Eiffel]]. This was the same building which years before was used as the location for their video of <U+201C>En La Ciudad De La Furia<U+201D>.<ref name="holas totales">{{cite web |url= http://www2.lavoz.com.ar/07/09/22/secciones/espectaculos/nota.asp?nota_id=117057 |title= Holas Totales |author=Arrascaeta, Germ<U+00E1>n |date=September 22, 2007 |work= | language = Spanish |publisher= La Voz del Interior |accessdate=December 11, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=" Club Musseum">{{cite web |url=http://www.clubmuseum.com.ar/disco.php |title= Club Musseum |author= |date= |work= Sitio Oficial del Club Musseum | language = Spanish |publisher= |accessdate= }}</ref> They surprised those there with a mini concert of two songs, <U+201C>Sobredosis de TV<U+201D> and <U+201C>En La Ciudad de La Furia,<U+201D> played in their original form. The song were played solely by the three of them. During the press conference the trio clarified that after the tour they intend on resuming their individual pursuits.

[[File:Soda Santiago 1.JPG|thumb|left|"We Saw You Return." A picture of the show at the [[:es:Estadio Nacional de Chile|Julio Mart<U+00ED>nez Stadium]] in [[Santiago, Chile]] on the 24th of October of [[2007]].]]

The tour was scheduled to begin on October 19 at [[Estadio Antonio Vespucio Liberti|River Plate Stadium]] in Buenos Aires, and originally only two concerts were scheduled as well as performances in several American countries. However, from the time the tickets went on sale it became apparent that the original program would be completely overwhelmed and that the band was faced with a huge continent-wide cultural event. The first two shows sold out in only 24 hours (a total of 90,000 tickets). The band quickly added one more show to the schedule,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sodastereo.com/noticias/record_historico.php | title = R<U+00E9>cord Hist<U+00F3>rico | date = 2007-06-13 | accessdate = 2007-06-10 | work = Soda Stereo official website | language = Spanish |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070808011746/http://sodastereo.com/noticias/record_historico.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-08-08}}</ref> and after three days, the tickets for the first three shows were sold out, so two more shows were added.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sodastereo.com/noticias/nuevas_funciones.php | title = Nuevas Funciones | date = 2007-06-15 | accessdate = 2007-06-10 | work = Soda Stereo official website | language = Spanish |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070626013228/http://sodastereo.com/noticias/nuevas_funciones.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-06-26}}</ref>

Finally on the 19th of October 2007, the time came for the triumphant return of Soda Stereo at the [[Estadio Antonio Vespucio Liberti|River Plate Stadium]] in Argentina. A massive banner that contained a large sentence with the name of their songs intertwined was unveiled.<ref name="">{{cite web |url= http://www.universo.cl/prontus_universo/site/artic/20071020/pags/20071020233904.html |title= Diez a<U+00F1>os despu<U+00E9>s<U+2026> fue un temblor en la ciudad de la furia |author=Costas, Carlos |date=September 20, 2007 |work= | language = Spanish |publisher=Radio Universo |accessdate=December 20, 2007}}</ref>

The band was accompanied by one of the main <U+201C>fourth Soda<U+2019>s<U+201D> [[Tweety Gonzalez]] (keyboards), as well as [[Leandro Fresco]] (keyboards, percussion, and backing vocals), and [[Leo Garcia]] on guitars and backing vocals. The concert lasted more than three hours. Soda played a total of 28 songs. The show opened with a recording of <U+201C>Algun Dia<U+201D> their cover of [[Queen (band)|Queen's]] <U+201C>Someday One Day<U+201D> meanwhile images of the history of Soda Stereo appeared in the background.

The expected amount of fans attending the five shows was more than 300,000, making Soda Stereo one of the most watched public events in the history of Argentina. Soda became the only band to play more than five times in the Estadio Monumental in Argentina in a single tour. Me Ver<U+00E1>s Volver featured 22 concerts throughout America including three shows in the US -all but two were sold out[42].

[[File:1799879382 b8d5b770c6 o.jpg|thumb|left|October 27, 2007 [[Estadio Modelo Alberto Spencer|Alberto Spencer National Stadium]] in [[Guayaquil]] (Ecuador). The public awaits the return of Soda Stereo.]]

In October 2007 Sony/BMG released Comfort Y M<U+00FA>sica Para Volar on DVD. The DVD included all of the songs recorded for the MTV unplugged session.

On the 21st of December 2007 the last concert was held at the [[Estadio Antonio Vespucio Liberti|River Plate Stadium]] in Buenos Aires. Three extra songs were played for this show, <U+201C>Si No Fuera Por,<U+201D> <U+201C>Terapia de Amor Intensiva,<U+201D> and <U+201C>Lo Que Sangra (La C<U+00FA>pula).<U+201D> The band was joined by Andrea <U+00C1>lvarez for <U+201C>Picnic en el 4B<U+201D>, Richard Coleman for <U+201C>No Existes<U+201D>, Fabi<U+00E1>n <U+201C>Zorrito V<U+00F6>n" Quintiero for <U+201C>Danza Rota<U+201D> and <U+201C>Profugos<U+201D>, Carlos Alomar for <U+201C>Lo Que Sangra (La C<U+00FA>pula)<U+201D> and <U+201C>Terapia de Amor Intensiva,<U+201D> and Gillespie for <U+201C>Signos<U+201D> and <U+201C>Fue.<U+201D> Cerati returned to use his famous expression <U+201C>gracias totales,<U+201D> and after playing <U+201C>De Musica Ligera.<U+201D> Finally, Cerati played the riff of <U+201C>Sueles Dejarme Solo<U+201D> and smashed his guitar.<ref name="despidio">{{cite web |url= http://www.imagenanimal.com/?ad=index.php |title= Soda Stereo se Despidi<U+00F3> Ante Una Multitud  |author= |date= |work= |language= Spanish |publisher= Imagen Animal |accessdate=December 24, 2007 }}</ref>

[[File:Cristina Fernandez y Soda Stereo.jpg|thumb|Soda Stereo with the President of Argentina, [[Cristina Fern<U+00E1>ndez de Kirchner]], 2007.]]

==Solo work==
===Gustavo Cerati===
Cerati worked with Daniel Melero in his 1992 album ''Colores Santos'', he co-wrote and produced most of the songs and although the album was never formally presented, two singles were released, "Vuelta por el Universo" and "Hoy Ya No Soy Yo".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://cerati.com/proyectos/colores_santos | title = ''Colores Santos'' | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | work = [[Gustavo Cerati]] official website | language = Spanish }}</ref> Cerati's second solo album was ''Amor Amarillo'' (1993), it contained collaborations by Zeta Bosio and Cerati's (then) wife Cecilia Amen<U+00E1>bar.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sodastereo.com/labanda/html/gustavo2.html | title = Gustavo Cerati | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | work = Soda Stereo official website | language = Spanish | archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20050206134240/http://sodastereo.com/labanda/html/gustavo2.html | archivedate = 2005-02-06 }}</ref>

After Soda's separation, Cerati released the studio albums ''[[Amor Amarillo]]'' (1993), ''[[Bocanada]]'' (1999), ''[[+Bien]]'' (2001) and ''[[Siempre es Hoy|Siempre Es Hoy]]'' (2002). In 2002 he released ''[[11 Episodios Sinf<U+00F3>nicos]]'' that contained some Soda Stereo and solo songs played live with a symphony orchestra. Cerati's last release, ''[[Ah<U+00ED> Vamos]]!'', is considered as a back-to-basics return.<ref>{{cite web | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=r835875|pure_url=yes}} | title = ''Ah<U+00ED> Vamos'' > Overview | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | last = Birchmeier | first = Jason | work = [[Allmusic]] }}</ref> His last album to date is [[Fuerza Natural]], which changes several things about their previous albums and has been very well received by fans and critics.

Cerati was also featured in Shakira's song "The Day and the Time" in her album called Oral Fixation, Volume 2 in 2005. The Spanish version of this song is called "Dia Especial" and can be found in the 1st volume of Fijacion Oral.

===Zeta Bosio===
Bosio has had a low profile over the years. He is working with [http://www.proyectounder.com/ Proyecto Under], an online portal for musicians. He also produced albums with many bands, such as Aguirre and Peligrosos Gorriones.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sodastereo.com/labanda/html/zeta2.html | title = Zeta Bosio | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | work = Soda Stereo official website | language = Spanish | archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060504215204/http://sodastereo.com/labanda/html/zeta2.html | archivedate = 2006-05-04 }}</ref> In a recent interview, he declared that he has no interest to play in a band.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.desdeabajoweb.com.ar/zeta.htm | title = Zeta Bosio | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | last = Luna | first = Ver<U+00F3>nica | coauthors = Rodrigo Carretero | work = Desde Abajo | language = Spanish |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061216212138/http://www.desdeabajoweb.com.ar/zeta.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-12-16}}</ref> He is also the artistic director of an independent label, [http://www.alertadiscos.com/ Alerta Records].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.alertadiscos.com | title = Staff | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | work = Alerta! DISCOS | language = Spanish }}</ref>
In 1997 he produced ''Nacion Hip Hop'', a CD compilation of local underground rap artists that is considered{{By whom|date=November 2009}} the founding stone of Argentine's hip hop scene. He also worked closely with hip hop act Tumbas (who opened for Soda Stereo in their last concert) and DJ Tortuga, who later became part of the experimental hip hop trio [[Koxmoz]].

===Charly Alberti===
Alberti released only one studio album without Soda Stereo in 1994, ''Plum'', along with his then girlfriend, supermodel Deborah de Corral,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sodastereo.com/labanda/html/charly2.html | title = Charly Alberti | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | work = Soda Stereo official website | language = Spanish | archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060504215211/http://sodastereo.com/labanda/html/charly2.html | archivedate = 2006-05-04 }}</ref> and since 1997 Alberti became interested in informatics, he was involved in running his company Cybrel Digital Entertainment, that aimed at generating and implementing content based technologies. He was named an Applemaster for his contributions to the music world.<ref name="alberti">{{cite web | url = http://www.charlyalberti.com/bioabajo.htm | title = Biograf<U+00ED>a | accessdate = 2007-01-04 | work = [[Charly Alberti]] official website | language = Spanish |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070319054736/http://www.charlyalberti.com/bioabajo.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-03-19}}</ref>

In 1998, he started two new projects, [http://www.urlmag.com URL Magazine], a culture magazine, and [http://www.urlrecords.com URL Records], a discographic label. He is also the founder of [http://www.yeyeye.com YeYeYe] and [http://musike.com Musike], two portals about music and entertainment.<ref name="alberti" />

Alberti recently formed another rock band with his brother, Andr<U+00E9>s Alberti, and recorded their first album named as the band, ''MOLE''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mole.la/ | title = MOLE | work = Mole official website | accessdate = 2007-08-11}}</ref> Alberti stated that he does not want Mole's sound to sound like Soda Stereo, he wants "Mole to live by itself."<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.clarin.com/diario/2007/05/02/espectaculos/c-00811.htm | title = Charly Alberti: "Ser un ex Soda facilita las cosas" | work = [[Clar<U+00ED>n (newspaper)|Clar<U+00ED>n]] | date = 2007-05-02 | first = Gaspar | last = Zimerman | language = Spanish | accessdate = 2007-08-11}}</ref>

==Legacy==
Soda Stereo has left a strong legacy among Spanish language musicians both in the rock scene and outside.
{{cquote|I have been a Cerati fan all my life when he was part of Soda Stereo and before I met him I had already gone to three of his concerts. Both Gustavo [Cerati] and [[Santana]] have enriched me, they are my little wonders.| ||[[Shakira]]<ref>Original quote: ''Toda mi vida he sido fan de Cerati cuando <U+00E9>l formaba parte de Soda Stereo y antes de conocerlo ya hab<U+00ED>a ido a tres de sus conciertos. Tanto Gustavo como Santana me han enriquecido, son mis peque<U+00F1>os milagros.'' 2006 http://www.cronica.com.mx/nota.php?id_nota=254425</ref>}}

{{cquote|Soda Stereo is one of the most emblematic bands in Latin America.| ||[[Gustavo Santaolalla]]<ref>url=http://www.netjoven.pe/noticias/5446/Gustavo-Santaolalla--quot-Soda-Stereo-es-emblematica-quot.html</ref>}}

{{cquote|"El temblor" was the first song of theirs that I heard, it was the first one to be heard in Colombia. I really dig [the reunion]. Why not, if they are alive? They are totally a legend. They have made history for all Latin American youths, and to see them toghether again, well, will be a great, great event.| ||[[Juanes]]<ref name=Juanes>[http://espanol.news.yahoo.com/s/ap/070919/entretenimiento/esp_mus_soda_stereo Yahoo News], [http://www.imagenanimal.com/foro/index.php?s=79f444ffd04ad75a7564090fb5da49bb&showtopic=2450 Imagen Animal]</ref>}}

{{cquote|Soda Stereo is a wonderful group. I'm very happy for [the 2007 reunion tour]. They are one of the best Latin rock groups.| ||[[Juan Luis Guerra]]<ref name=Juanes/>}}

